In this process,the mixed metal precursors connect with the oxygen-containing groups of GO by electrostatic interaction and the precursors uniformly nest on both sides of GO sheets.Then the as-prepared metal precursors/GO composites are annealed at $9 0 0 ^ { \circ } \mathrm { C }$ under $\Nu _ { 2 }$ atmosphere.Due to the reducibility of graphene under high temperature,the mixed metal precursors merger to CoNiCuMgZn HEA nanoparticle.Benefiting from the pinning effect between graphene sheet and HEA,the HEA nanoparticles uniformly anchor on graphene without excessive aggregation.Meanwhile,the 2D holey structure,which comes from the consumed graphene in the reduction process, provides a large amount of hole voids for the diffusion of the electrolyte and the products, leading to enhanced HER catalytic performance.

Great interests have been focused on high entropy alloys,a new class of single-phase solid solution materials, because of their unique physical and chemical properties.Herein, CoNiCuMgZn high entropy alloy (HEA) has been homogeneously embedded onto ultrathin two-dimensional (2D) holey graphene conducting substrates via a simple anchoring and allying strategy.During the growth of the HEA,graphene oxide is employed as both direct template and reductant.By modulating the initial input amounts of metal sources,the particle sizes of HEA can be finely regulated from 40 to 200 \mathrm{nm} .Benefiting from the synergistic effect between the excellent electronic conductivity of graphene and the abundant catalytic sites of HEA particles,the obtained material displays remarkable catalytic activity and stability for hydrogen evolution reaction compared to previous reported nonnoble-metal catalysts.The density functional theory calculation unveils that the unique embedded structure of HEA onto graphene benefits to the \mathrm{H^{*}} sorption and promotes the catalytic kinetics.

Furthermore,the well-defined dense holey structure of graphene skeleton facilitated the penetration of electrolyte and promoted the fast mass transfer of reactants/products,thereby the unique structure leaded to enhanced HER performance.The long-term stability isa key performance criterion of catalysts for their actual application in HER process.Fig.5b showed the comparison of the 1st and 1000th polarization curves of the HEA $4 0 @ \mathrm { C } ,$ 、it was found that both curves were nearly overlapped, which illuminated the excellent durability in a long-term HER process.Moreover,the stability of $\mathrm { H E A - } 4 0 @ \mathrm { C }$ was evaluated using the chronoamperometric measurement in 1 MKOH with a current density of $1 0 \mathrm { m A } { \cdot } \mathrm { c m } ^ { - 2 }$ .As shown in Fig.5c,a stable catalytic performance with less than ${ \bf 1 0 \% }$ degradation of the initial current could be maintained after $^ \mathrm { 1 0 0 ~ h }$ electrolysis,indicating the prominent structural stability for HER in alkaline environment (Fig.S8)[44].
